# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bacilli
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bacilli/acholeplasmatales] Etymology: The names Acholeplasmataceae and Acholetoplasmatales are derived from the Greek *a* = not, *cholè* = bile and *plasma* = anything moulded or formed.
[src:bacilli/acholeplasmatales] Species in the order Acholeplasmatales can grow in a medium without cholesterol, unlike species in the order Mycoplasmatales.
[src:bacilli/acholeplasmatales] Cholesterol, a sterol, is an important component of the cell membrane of mycoplasmas, whereas in acholeplasmas and in bacteria in general it is absent.
[src:bacilli/acholeplasmatales] Members of Acholeplasmatales are facultative anaerobic.
[src:bacilli/acholeplasmatales] They are parasites or commensals of vertebrates, insects, or plants; some are saprophytes.
[src:bacilli/acholeplasmatales] Phytoplasmas colonize the phloem sieve elements of vascular plants, causing diseases.
[src:bacilli/acholeplasmatales] They are transmitted by sap-sucking insects (primarily leafhoppers, planthoppers, and psyllids ), living in the gut, haemolymph, salivary gland and other organs.
[src:bacilli/acholeplasmatales] Like other mollicutes, they show a high host specificity.
[src:bacilli/acholeplasmatales] In the first taxonomy of Mollicutes, the classification was based on requiring or not requiring cholesterol for growth.
[src:bacilli/acholeplasmatales] The old order Mycoplasmatales consisted of two families: Mycoplasmataceae, which requires cholesterol, and the sterol-nonrequiring Acholeplasmataceae.
[src:bacilli/acholeplasmatales] In view of the many properties in which the acholeplasmas distinguish from species in Mycoplasmataceae and Spiroplasmataceae, Freundt et al. proposed in 1984 to elevate the family Acholeplasmataceae to the ordinal rank Acholeplasmatales, thus separating it from Mycoplasmatales.
[src:bacilli/acholeplasmatales] In 1987, the division in sterol requiring and not requiring changed with the addition of a third order, Anaeroplasmatales, taking into account that dependence on anaerobic growth conditions is an important characteristic.
[src:bacilli/acidimicrobiia] The ***Acidimicrobiia*** are a class of Actinomycetota, in which three families, eight genera, and nine species have been described, *Acidimicrobium ferrooxidans* is the type species of the order.
[src:bacilli/acidimicrobiia] The currently accepted taxonomy is based on the List of Prokaryotic names with Standing in Nomenclature (LPSN) and National Center for Biotechnology Information (NCBI).
[src:bacilli/acidobacteriia] The "**Acidobacteriia**" is a class of Acidobacteriota.
[src:bacilli/acidobacteriia] The currently accepted taxonomy is based on the List of Prokaryotic names with Standing in Nomenclature and National Center for Biotechnology Information (NCBI).
[src:bacilli/acidobacteriia] Numbered orders do not yet have any cultured representatives.
[src:bacilli/acidobacteriota] Members of this phylum are physiologically diverse, and can be found in a variety of environments including soil, decomposing wood, hot springs, oceans, caves, and metal-contaminated soils.
[src:bacilli/acidobacteriota] The members of this phylum are particularly abundant in soil habitats representing up to 52% of the total bacterial community.
[src:bacilli/acidobacteriota] Environmental factors such as pH and nutrients have been seen to drive Acidobacteriota dynamics.
[src:bacilli/acidobacteriota] Many Acidobacteriota are acidophilic, including the first described member of the phylum, *Acidobacterium capsulatum*.
[src:bacilli/acidobacteriota] There is much that is unknown about Acidobacteria both in their form and function.
[src:bacilli/acidobacteriota] Thus, this is a growing field of microbiology.
[src:bacilli/acidobacteriota] Some of this uncertainty can be attributed to the difficulty with which these bacteria are grown in the laboratory.
[src:bacilli/acidobacteriota] There has been recent success in propagation by using low concentrations of nutrients in combination with high amounts of CO2, yet, progress is still quite slow.
[src:bacilli/acidobacteriota] These new methods have only allowed approximately 30% of subdivisions to have species documented.
[src:bacilli/acidobacteriota] Additionally, many of the samples sequenced do not have taxonomic names as they have not yet been fully characterized.
[src:bacilli/acidobacteriota] This area of study is a very current topic, and scientific understanding is expected to grow and change as new information comes to light.
[src:bacilli/acidobacteriota] Other notable species are *Holophaga foetida*, *Geothrix fermentans*, *Acanthopleuribacter pedis* and *Bryobacter aggregatus*.
[src:bacilli/acidobacteriota] Since they have only recently been discovered and the large majority have not been cultured, the ecology and metabolism of these bacteria is not well understood.
[src:bacilli/acidobacteriota] However, these bacteria may be an important contributor to ecosystems, since they are particularly abundant within soils.
[src:bacilli/acidobacteriota] Members of subdivisions 1, 4, and 6 are found to be particularly abundant in soils.
[src:bacilli/acidobacteriota] As well as their natural soil habitat, unclassified subdivision 2 Acidobacteriota have also been identified as a contaminant of DNA extraction kit reagents, which may lead to their erroneous appearance in microbiota or metagenomic datasets.
[src:bacilli/acidobacteriota] Members of subdivision 1 have been found to dominate in low pH conditions.
[src:bacilli/acidobacteriota] Additionally, Acidobacteriota from acid mine drainage have been found to be more adapted to acidic pH conditions (pH 2–3) compared to Acidobacteriota from soils, potentially due to cell specialization and enzyme stability.
[src:bacilli/acidobacteriota] The G+C content of Acidobacteria genomes are consistent within their subdivisions - above 60% for group V fragments and roughly 10% lower for group III fragments.
[src:bacilli/acidobacteriota] The majority of Acidobacteriota are considered aerobes.
[src:bacilli/acidobacteriota] There are some Acidobacteriota that are considered anaerobes within subdivision 8 and subdivision 23.
[src:bacilli/acidobacteriota] It has been found that some strains of Acidobacteriota originating from soils have the genomic potential to respire oxygen at atmospheric and sub-atmospheric concentrations.
[src:bacilli/acidobacteriota] Members of the *Acidobacteriota* phylum have been considered oligotrophic bacteria due to high abundances in low organic carbon environments.
[src:bacilli/acidobacteriota] However, the variation in this phylum may indicate that they may not have the same ecological strategy.
[src:bacilli/acidobacteriota] The first species, *Acidobacterium capsulatum*, of this phylum was discovered in 1991.
[src:bacilli/acidobacteriota] However, Acidobacteriota were not recognized as a distinct clade until 1997, and were not recognized as a phylum until 2012.
[src:bacilli/acidobacteriota] In an effort to further classify Acidobacteria, 16S rRNA gene regions were sequenced from many different strains.
[src:bacilli/acidobacteriota] These sequences lead to the formation of subdivisions within the phyla.
[src:bacilli/acidobacteriota] Today, there are 26 accepted subdivisions recognized in the Ribosomal Database Project.
[src:bacilli/acidobacteriota] Much of this variety comes from populations of acidobacteria found in soils contaminated with uranium.
[src:bacilli/acidobacteriota] Therefore, most of the known species in this phyla are concentrated in a few of the subdivisions, the largest being #1.
[src:bacilli/acidobacteriota] Most of these microbes are aerobes, and they are all heterotrophic.
[src:bacilli/acidobacteriota] Subdivision 1 contains 11 of the known genera in addition to the majority of the species that have been able to be cultivated thus far.
[src:bacilli/acidobacteriota] Within the 22 known genera, there are 40 conclusive species.
[src:bacilli/acidobacteriota] The genera are divided amongst subdivisions 3, 4, 8, 10, 23, and 1.
[src:bacilli/acidobacteriota] As the Acidobateria are a developing area of microbiology, it is hypothesized that these numbers will change drastically with further study.
[src:bacilli/acidobacteriota] Some members of subdivision 1 are able to use D-glucose, D-xylose, and lactose as carbon sources, but are unable to use fucose or sorbose.
[src:bacilli/acidobacteriota] Members of subdivision 1 also contain enzymes such as galactosidases used in the breakdown of sugars.
[src:bacilli/acidobacteriota] Members of subdivision 4 have been found to use chitin as a carbon source.
[src:bacilli/acidobacteriota] Despite the presence of genetic information generally known to encode for carbohydrate processing machinery in various genera of Acidobacteria, several experimental studies have demonstrated the inability to break down various polysaccharides.
[src:bacilli/acidobacteriota] Cellulose is the main component of plant cell walls and a seemingly opportune resource for carbon.
[src:bacilli/acidobacteriota] However, only a single species across all subdivisions has been shown to process it, *Telmactobacter bradus* from subvision 1.
[src:bacilli/acidobacteriota] Researchers believe that an additional factor in the lack of understanding of carbon degradation by acidobacteria may stem from the present limited ability to provide adequate cultivation conditions.
[src:bacilli/acidobacteriota] To study the natural behavior of these bacteria, they must grow and live in a controlled, observable environment.
[src:bacilli/acidobacteriota] If such a habitat cannot be provided, recorded data cannot reliably report on the activity of the microbes in question.
[src:bacilli/acidobacteriota] Therefore, the inconsistencies between genome sequence based predictions and observed carbon processes may be explained by present study methods.
[src:bacilli/acidobacteriota] There has been no clear evidence that Acidobacteriota are involved in nitrogen-cycle processes such as nitrification, denitrification, or nitrogen fixation.
[src:bacilli/acidobacteriota] However, *Geothrix fermantans* was shown to be able to reduce nitrate and contained the norB gene.
[src:bacilli/acidobacteriota] The NorB gene was also identified in *Koribacter verstailis* and *Solibacter usitatus*.
[src:bacilli/acidobacteriota] In addition, the presence of the nirA gene has been observed in members of subdivision 1.
[src:bacilli/acidobacteriota] Additionally, to date, all genomes have been described to directly uptake ammonium via ammonium channel transporter family genes.
[src:bacilli/acidobacteriota] Acidobacteriota can use both inorganic and organic nitrogen as their nitrogen sources.
[src:bacilli/acidulidesulfobacteriota] Acidulidesulfobacteriota are ecologically significant in biogeochemical cycling, especially with respect to sulfur and iron.
[src:bacilli/acidulidesulfobacteriota] Their genomes show evidence of interaction with viruses, which can influence host metabolic functions including folate biosynthesis and sulfur pathways.
[src:bacilli/actinomycetota] The **Actinomycetota** (previously known as **"Actinobacteria"**) are a diverse phylum of Gram-positive bacteria with high guanine-cytosine content (GC content or G+C content).
[src:bacilli/actinomycetota] They are of great importance to land flora because of their contributions to soil systems.
[src:bacilli/actinomycetota] In soil, they help decompose organic matter of dead organisms so the molecules can be taken up anew by plants.
[src:bacilli/actinomycetota] While this role is also played by fungi, actinomycetota are much smaller and likely do not occupy the same ecological niche.
[src:bacilli/actinomycetota] In this role, the colonies often grow extensive mycelia, as fungi do, and the name of an important order of the phylum, Actinomycetales (the actinomycetes), reflects that they were long believed to be fungi.
[src:bacilli/actinomycetota] Some soil actinomycetota (such as *Frankia*) live symbiotically with the plants whose roots pervade the soil, fixing nitrogen for the plants in exchange for access to some of the plant's saccharides.
[src:bacilli/actinomycetota] Other species, such as many members of the genus *Mycobacterium*, are important pathogens.
[src:bacilli/actinomycetota] Beyond the great interest in Actinomycetota for their soil role, much is yet to be learned about them.
[src:bacilli/actinomycetota] Although currently understood primarily as soil bacteria, they might be more abundant in fresh waters.
[src:bacilli/actinomycetota] Actinomycetota is one of the dominant bacterial phyla and contains one of the largest of bacterial genera: *Streptomyces*.
[src:bacilli/actinomycetota] *Streptomyces* and other actinomycetota are major contributors to biological buffering of soils.
[src:bacilli/actinomycetota] They are also the source of many antibiotics.
[src:bacilli/actinomycetota] Bacteria of the Actinomycetota genus *Bifidobacterium* are the most common in the microbiome of human infants.
[src:bacilli/actinomycetota] Although adults have fewer bifidobacteria, intestinal bifidobacteria help maintain the mucosal barrier and reduce lipopolysaccharides in the intestine.
[src:bacilli/actinomycetota] Although some of the largest and most complex bacterial cells belong to the Actinomycetota, the group of marine Actinomarinales has been described as possessing the smallest free-living prokaryotic cells.
[src:bacilli/actinomycetota] Some Siberian or Antarctic biofilms of these bacteria are said to have the longest lifespan of any organism on Earth, frozen in permafrost at around half a million years ago.
[src:bacilli/actinomycetota] Most actinomycetota of medical or economic significance are in class Actinomycetia, and belong to the order Actinomycetales.
[src:bacilli/actinomycetota] While many of these cause disease in humans, *Streptomyces* is notable as a source of antibiotics.
[src:bacilli/actinomycetota] Of those actinomycetota not in the Actinomycetales, *Gardnerella* is one of the most researched.
[src:bacilli/actinomycetota] Classification of *Gardnerella* is controversial, and MeSH catalogues it as both a Gram-positive and Gram-negative organism.
[src:bacilli/actinomycetota] Actinomycetota-derived antibiotics that are important in medicine include aminoglycosides, anthracyclines, chloramphenicol, macrolides, tetracyclines, etc.
[src:bacilli/actinomycetota] Actinomycetota have high guanine and cytosine content in their DNA.
[src:bacilli/actinomycetota] The GC content of actinomycetota can be as high as 70%, though some may have a low GC content.
[src:bacilli/actinomycetota] Analysis of glutamine synthetase sequence has been suggested for phylogenetic analysis of the Actinomycetota.
[src:bacilli/bacilli] The name *Bacillus*, capitalized and italicized, refers to a specific genus of bacteria.
[src:bacilli/bacilli] The name Bacilli, capitalized but not italicized, can also refer to a less specific taxonomic group of bacteria that includes two orders, one of which contains the genus *Bacillus*.
[src:bacilli/bacilli] When the word is formatted with lowercase and not italicized, 'bacillus', it will most likely be referring to shape and not to the genus at all.
[src:bacilli/bacilli] Several related concepts make use of similar words, and the ambiguity can create considerable confusion.
[src:bacilli/bacilli] The term "*Bacillus*" (capitalized and italicized) is also the name of a genus (*Bacillus anthracis*) that, among many other genera, falls within the class Bacilli.
[src:bacilli/bacilli] The word "bacillus" (or its plural "bacilli", with a small b) is also a generic term to describe the morphology of any rod-shaped bacterium.
[src:bacilli/bacilli] This general term does not mean that the subject is a member of class Bacilli or genus *Bacillus*.
[src:bacilli/bacilli] Thus, it does not necessarily imply a similar group of characteristics.
[src:bacilli/bacilli] Not all members of class Bacilli are rod-shaped (*Staphylococcus* is spherical), and many other rod-shaped bacteria that do not fall within that class exist (e.g., *Clostridium* is rod-shaped but very different taxonomically).
[src:bacilli/bacilli] Moreover, the general term "bacillus" does not necessarily indicate the Gram-positive staining common to class Bacilli.
[src:bacilli/bacilli] For example, *E. coli* is a rod-shaped bacterium that can be described as "a bacillus", but it stains Gram-negative and does not belong to the genus *Bacillus* or the class Bacilli.
[src:bacilli/bacilli] Some microbiologists have forsaken the general "bacillus" term because of the confusion it can create.
[src:bacilli/bacilli] The currently accepted taxonomy based on the List of Prokaryotic names with Standing in Nomenclature (LPSN) and the National Center for Biotechnology Information (NCBI).
